&amp;E Executive News Filter</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:ghack"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Top of the News</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Protecting your personal data from abuse</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>People have asked how they can protect their personal data from being exploited in light of the recent discovery that more than 50 million Facebook users' information was accessed.</Para><Para>Short of deleting their Facebook account, users have really no way of preventing such abuses. But Facebook users can limit their exposure.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Cyber security firms Symantec, McAfee, Trend Micro and Kaspersky Lab detail how:</Para><Para>READ PRIVACY POLICIES</Para><Para>When installing new apps or programs, always read the terms and conditions, especially privacy policies. Look for clauses on information-gathering or sharing. If you are uncertain or uncomfortable with the terms and conditions, do not install the program.</Para><Para>BE SELECTIVE ABOUT DOWNLOADS</Para><Para>If you have never heard of the software maker, read its website carefully to learn about the technology and people behind it before downloading the app or software.</Para><Para>DELETE OLD DATA</Para><Para>Delete old posts and store the information in an external hard drive if you need to. Old data can help a stalker build a profile of you.</Para><Para>REVIEW PRIVACY SETTINGS</Para><Para>Facebook privacy settings often change, so it is good practice to review them frequently. You could minimise the information shared publicly by making sure that only friends can see your posts, pictures or tags from friends. You can also remove tags from friends if you are uncomfortable with the information shared.</Para><Para>AUDIT FACEBOOK APPS</Para><Para>Go to Account Settings in your Facebook app and click on the Apps tab to review what apps can be logged in with your Facebook account. Remove apps that are suspicious or which you no longer use.</Para><Para>DISABLE LOCATION ACCESS</Para><Para>Go to Account Settings in your Facebook app and click on the Location tab to disable location access. Also, do not use the "check-in" function in Facebook which exposes your location information.</Para><Para>DO NOT ACCEPT FRIENDS' REQUESTS WITHOUT CHECKING</Para><Para>It is easy for scammers to set up fake Facebook accounts. Do not accept a friend's request before verifying with the friend that the request is genuine. Do not add people you do not know as friends.</Para><Para>AVOID ONLINE PERSONALITY QUIZZES</Para><Para>Cambridge University researcher Aleksandr Kogan's personality-quiz app allegedly provided a backdoor for political consulting firm Cambridge Analytica to access some 50 million Facebook users' profiles.</Para><Para>The app was downloaded by 270,000 Facebook users, who unwittingly gave away data on their Facebook activities and friends' too, depending on their privacy settings. Irene Tham</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Irene Tham </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

